# `core/`

**No I/O:** no Flask, no DB drivers, no HTTP clients, no env reads as part of domain logic.

## Imports

**Forbidden:** `orchestrator_v4.infrastructure`, `orchestrator_v4.presentation` (the folders `infrastructure/` and `presentation/` on disk).

## Need something from outside?

1. Add or use an interface in `core/ports/`.
2. Implement it under `infrastructure/`.
3. Pass the instance into the use case (argument or constructor)—not a global.

## Subfolders

- **`entities/`**: shapes and rules on those shapes. Wire shapes (persisted rows, JSON payloads, structured adapter returns) live here as a `TypedDict` or a frozen `@dataclass` — never inline in a port. Use `TypedDict(..., total=False)` for partial-update payloads.
- **`use_cases/`**: one user-visible action per module; calls entities and ports only.
- **`ports/`**: typed interfaces only. `Protocol` or `abc.ABC`. Every method names its argument and return types with entity shapes — never `dict[str, Any]` or `**kwargs: Any`.

## Naming

- Prefer interview-domain words (session, turn, roster).
- Avoid empty job-title names: `Service`, `Manager`, `Handler`, `Helper`, `Model`, `Item`.

## Junk-defense at the port boundary

When a port returns a value a use case will act on, validate every field in a pure entity function before the use case reads it. A bug in an adapter, a malformed remote response, or a future change to the adapter must not be able to widen behavior. The pure function at the boundary is the contract; the adapter is not trusted.
